content.description: Gear protected mid fifth climbing leads to 3 bolts on a prow.  Climbing is consistently 5.9-5.10 past the bolts, with crux near the third bolt.  A marginal TCU can be wiggled in above the last bolt to "protect" the exit.
content.protection: mostly quickdraws with some optional mid size cams for the start and a blue or yellow tcu for the finish.  Gear protected start can apparently be bypassed via ledge on the right.
content.location: Far right side of right hand JY crag slab.

content.description: Start low on side pull and crimp, hit the sloper and climb the left facing rail.
content.location: Park in the pullout past 8 mile camp ground.  Fallow the trail up to the right.

content.description: This climb shares the same start as Barbie Mud Flaps at the base of the arete.  After a few feet, move right and follow a line of bolts up past a few cracks where you can place gear.
content.protection: Gear to 1.5", 3 bolts, fixed rap station

content.description: Thin face climbing past 2 bolts and a fixed pin leads to a small puzzle at the roof.  Pull up into the solid crack above and climb up to a leftward traverse around another roof.  Finish by pulling right over a smaller roof, to a sparsely-protected face and the chains.
content.protection: Gear to 2", 2 bolts, 1 fixed pin.  The second bolt was missing its hanger and I looped a wired stopper over it.
content.location: Starts on the face, just left of the big corner.  Shares the same finish as Earthmover.

content.description: Climb the face past two bolts and a patch of grass, to the dirty corner below the roof.  Clip some more bolts while skirting the roof on the left, and finish up the crack above.
content.location: Under the left side of the big roof.

content.description: Good for Nothing is actually good for something, a fun route with some tricky moves, mantle, horizontal crack, face climb up to ramp leading left to anchor
content.protection:
gear to 1 1/2", 1 bolt, 1 fixed pin

Bolted anchor
content.location: center of main left side slab.

content.description:
Climb the big dirty corner, then make two fun leftward traverses under roofs.  The finish bumps righward over another small roof, to sparsely protected face climbing, and then the chains.  Watch rope drag, and don't get lost.

This route would be excellent if it were cleaner.
content.protection: Gear to 2".  Save a finger-sized cam to plug into the horizontal crack at the bottom of the final face (I used an orange TCU).
content.location: Starts in big corner that splits the crag.  Shares the same finish as New Frustrations.

climbs.name: Dirtbag Direct
climbs.fa: Russ Ricketts, Sean Woods, Viktor Kramer 2009

content.description:
Climb cool slab moves with bolts for protection to a horizontal break between the 3rd & 4th bolt which takes a ~.5 inch cam well and makes the crux feel much safer.

This section of rock between the 3rd and 4th bolt is definitely the crux and may have crumbled a bit in the last few years. I climbed this in 2012 and it felt spot on for 5.9, I climbed it in the early summer of 2018 and it felt slightly tougher and again in July 2018 and I backed off because it felt super thin and sketchy. I'll admit it could have been the heat but It still seemed like holds were a bit smaller and harder to use.
content.location: On the left part of the main wall in the shade of some maple trees. Right of Janetors of Justice.

content.description: Crux is thin face climbing and arete slapping after 2nd bolt.  rest of climb is much easier, but still fun.  After clipping last bolt, move up and right to shared anchor.  No stars in guidebook, but certainly deserving of at least 1 or 2.
content.protection: Mostly bolts, with a very useful nut between 1st and 2nd bolt, and maybe a cam before first bolt and after last bolt.  A set of cams to 1" and some nuts should suffice.
content.location: The left hand arete of the right hand slab on JY crag.  First bolt is above a horizontal crack.

content.description:
Obvious splitter hand to finger crack on right side of crag.  Starts out easy, steps left to excellent left trending finger locks, finishes with crux thin face moves after crack pinches down.  Save a small cam (red C3 size) to protect crack prior to crux face moves.  A bit soft for 10b.

Also known as Air Force Crack.
content.protection: Standard rack to 2" should be fine.  Nuts would work well too. Two bolt anchor at top is shared with 4-5 routes on same slab.
content.location: Start in easy hand crack on right side of crag.  Rap route.
